{"key":"processedPost-11766092","value":{"id":11766092,"first":11764015,"last":12118516,"when":1262647368,"utime":"01/05/10 01:22 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>pblcenmy1 said:</b><br />senescence deals mostly with aging after full maturity.&nbsp; You could clone a young commercial shitake and get good results.&nbsp; <br /></blockquote><br /><br />No, senescence has nothing to do with full maturity, whatever that is.&nbsp; <br /><br />Senescence has to do with the number of cell divisions the mycelium has accomplished since germinating from spores.&nbsp; With any commercial mushroom crop, they'll have grown the grain spawn nearly to senescence before using it to inoculate the fruiting substrate.&nbsp; You can't clone a young commercial shiitake and get good results, period.&nbsp; You'll get a dish like noobies that grows 1\" and then stops, or in a best case scenario, you'll waste four months to get one or two mushrooms that won't even be enough for one meal.<br /><br />Order a culture from a reputable supplier.&nbsp; I like the 75 strain from aloha medicinals.<br />RR","title":"Re: Shiitake cloning","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}